1. DEFINITION
Hamming distance between two equal-length strings (or equal-length bit-vectors) is the number of positions at which the corresponding symbols differ.

2. FORMAL SPECIFICATION
Input: two sequences A and B of length n over the same alphabet.
Output: integer d where d = |{ i in [0..n-1] : A[i] != B[i] }|.
Properties: non-negative integer, symmetric, equals zero iff A == B.

3. USE CASES AND CONSTRAINTS
- Error detection/correction: minimum Hamming distance of a code defines the number of detectable and correctable errors (t = floor((d_min-1)/2) correctable).
- Similarity measures: binary strings, fixed-length encodings, DNA sequences when aligned without gaps.
- Requirement: inputs must be same length; otherwise define behavior explicitly (pad/truncate or undefined).

4. ALGORITHMIC COMPUTATION
- For binary vectors: XOR the two bit-vectors then count set bits of result (popcount).
- For strings over arbitrary alphabets: iterate index i from 0 to n-1, increment counter when A[i] != B[i].
- For large bit-strings stored in machine words: process in word-sized chunks (e.g., 32/64-bit), XOR, then popcount per word, sum results.

5. COMPLEXITY
Time: O(n) comparisons or O(n / w) word-XOR+popcount operations when using machine-word parallelism (w = word size in bits).
Space: O(1) additional memory beyond inputs and counters.

6. SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS
- When using Unicode strings: ensure consistent normalization and iteration over code points (not code units) for logical symbol comparison. Use codePoint-aware iteration when required.
- For streaming comparison where lengths differ: decide semantic (report mismatch for extra trailing symbols or stop at min-length) and document chosen policy.

7. REFERENCE DETAILS (APIs, PATTERNS)
- Binary pattern (word-based):
  for each word index j: diff = wordA[j] XOR wordB[j]; count += popcount(diff)
- popcount implementations: use built-in CPU instruction (POPCNT) or software fallback using Kernighan loop: while(x) { x &= x-1; ++count; }
- For JavaScript typed arrays: load as BigUint64Array (if available) or DataView to read 64-bit words; for Node.js native C++ addons use builtin popcount for performance.

